Remarks:
Eremiaphila ammonita
can be recognized by the extending blackish brown band of the hind wing, which covers all of it except its yellow borders. This species was described from Amman ( Jordan ) (
Uvarov, 1933
). Also, it was incorrectly recorded from Palestine under the name
Eremiaphila genei
by
Uvarov ( 1923 )
. The female Holotype was collected by Buxton in
25 .VIII. 1921
from Amman and was kept in the British Museum (
Marshall , 1975
). So far, this species appears to be endemic to Jordan and Palestine . It appears usually from April to September. It was common in cultivated lands around fields planted with barley and also on soil covered with many white small stones near Ash Shawbak. High level of cannibalism was observed among the nymphs in rearing cages.
